{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522784"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:48:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:48:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13845"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13845"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.1,0.03,0.12,0.38]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6462"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53800"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6462"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13845"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39255"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2393"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12778"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14032"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16014"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53800"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about her fingernails. She reports that several of her nails have been separating from the nail bed over the past two months. She had regular manicures and thought she was reacting to a new nail product so had ceased having manicures one month prior. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Inspection of her hands reveals separation of the nail plate from the nail bed on nine fingernails, with a yellowish discoloration of the affected areas (Image). There are no signs of infection. The rest of her skin examination shows a few small, scaley plaques on her elbows.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral terbinafine","Topical tacrolimus","Intralesional corticosteroid injection","Oral methotrexate","Topical calcipotriol/betamethasone combination"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with psoriatic onycholysis, evidenced by the separating of the nail from the nail plate. This can occur in fifty per cent of patients with psoriasis. This may present variably with nail pitting, onycholysis, salmon patches, leukonychia, subungual hyperkeratosis or splinter haemorrhages.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate initial management in this case would be \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical calcipotriol/betamethasone combination\u003C/strong\u003E. This combination therapy has shown efficacy is generally well-tolerated. It addresses both the inflammatory and hyperproliferative aspects of psoriatic nail disease. In this case it would be low likelihood to be successful given the extensive nail involvement, however should be trialled first given the minimal disease elsewhere and side effect profile of systemic treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral terbinafine\u003C/strong\u003E is an antifungal medication typically used to treat onychomycosis (fungal nail infections). While onychomycosis can sometimes resemble onycholysis, the patient\u0027s examination findings on the elbows are more suggestive of psoriasis and the absence of signs of fungal infection make this treatment inappropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical tacrolimus\u003C/strong\u003E can be used off-label for psoriasis, particularly in sensitive areas. However, it is not a first-line treatment for nail psoriasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntralesional corticosteroid injection\u003C/strong\u003E may be used as second-line treatment when there has been no response to topical treatments. It also carries risks such as pain, atrophy of the nail bed, and systemic absorption of steroids. Therefore, it would not be the most appropriate first-line treatment in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral methotrexate\u003C/strong\u003E can be used for moderate to severe psoriasis affecting large areas of skin or causing significant impact on quality of life. While it can improve nail psoriasis, because it is a systemic treatment rather than localised, it would be overly aggressive for this patient who has limited nail involvement and otherwise mild skin disease who has not trailed other treatments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to topical treatment, the patient should be educated about proper nail care and using emollients. They should avoid manicures or similar causes of trauma to the nails, and to keep the nails short with nail clippers. If the condition does not improve with topical therapy, or if it worsens or spreads to more nails, reassessment and consideration of other treatment options, including systemic therapies, may be necessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Psoriatic onycholysis is a common nail manifestation of psoriasis.","Treatment of psoriatic onycholysis involves a combination of topical therapies, systemic treatments for severe cases, and patient education on nail care."],"references":["Psoriasis In: Therapeutic Guidelines [online]. 2022; accessed 2024 Sep 10. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au","Tendais-Almeida J, Aguiar F, Torres T. Nail pitting and onycholysis. Australian Family Physician. 2016:45(3). Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2016/march/nail-pitting-and-onycholysis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39255"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13845"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20794"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20794"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/EX3wUCzsnfXsgk2eNGoVCQFGF1tL99.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/EX3wUCzsnfXsgk2eNGoVCQFGF1tL99.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39255"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-26T20:12:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-26T20:13:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6462"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53800"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"posit